rult, az volt a felfogasuk: "mit csinaljunk egy  millio 'mezei zsidoval'?"Vagyis a nyomorultja, a szegenyek, a keservesen dolgozok tomege  nem kell, annak nincs penze, ezekbol nem lehet profitot csinalni...Igy aztan egyenes ut vezetett a nemetorszagi zsidok sorsahoz, amit a  gazdag zsidok segitettek elo es kozvetve felelosek voltak az  elpusztitasukban.Most MONUS ARON kiadja otthon HITLER ADOLF: MEIN KAMPF cimu  konyvet, ami mar majdnem minden orszagban szabadon kaphato es  arusithato. [Soros Budapesti boltjaban is kaphato (angolul), de az  Interneten barki altal tanulmanyozhatok a boseges kivonatok: pl.   http://www.missouri.edu/~c545573/wcs/hitler.htm  cimen].Amikor a riporter megkerdezte Monus Aront, mi a a celja a konyv  kiadasaval, azt valaszolta, az igazsagvagy vezeti, es nem igaz az a vad,  hogy ha a konyv megjelenik, majd tombolni fog az antiszemitizmus  es ver fog folyni az utcakon.  Azt is elmondta, Franciaorszagban  eppen a szabadkomuvesek akartak megakadalyozni a konyv  megjeleneset 1979-ben, de a Fellebbviteli Birosag megis  engedelyezte.  Nyilatkozatanak utolso mondatai szinte  korbacsuteskent hatnak, amikor azt mondja: "A szabadkomuvesek  tudtak, hogy Hitler mit akar [ugyanis Mein Kampf evekkel a  Holocaust elott jelent meg, es abban Hitler pontosan megirta, mire  keszul], es nekik erre volt szukseguk.  Igy kizsarolhattak IZRAEL  allam megalapitasat. Azota is allandoan zsaroljak az egesz vilagot.  Es  mindenki fejet hajt.  Magyarorszag is beallt a sorba.  Akik  megszavazzak ezeket a karteritesi penzeket, maguk is  szabadkomuvesek. Mint peldaul HORN GYULA".Az utsolso mondat teljes megertesehez tudni kell, hogy HORN Gyula  bocsanatot kert 1994-ben a magyarok neveben azoktol, es azok  utodjaitol, akiket, mint magyar allampolgarokat megfosztottak  emberi jogaiktol, majd meggyilkoltak oket a multban.  Persze ennek  a bocsanatkeresnek a hire, az otthoni liberalis sajto segitsegevel  gyorsan kijutott kulfoldre, es meg sem allt a Zsido Vilagszekhazig,  Amerikaban.  Ennek a "bocsanatkeresnek" tudhato be, hogy  megjelent a Zsido Vilagszovetseg fotitkara, IZRAEL SINGER  Magyarorszagon.  Targyalni jott es reszleteiben is kidolgozni -  mennyi lesz az a penz, ami az elpusztitott zsidok utan jar.Bar ez a nemzetkozi karpotlas mar megtortent mas oldalrol, viszont  Horn Gyula alazatos bocsanatkerese most raebresztette a Zsido  Vilagszovetseget, hogy lehet meg tovabbi penzeket kovetelni, ha a  magyarok beismerik alazatosan a zsidok ellen elkovetett  kegyetlensegeket.  Hiszen a szabadon megvalasztott miniszterelnok  adott ehhez zold fenyt!Tudott dolog az is, hogy addig a magyarorszagi zsido szervezetek csak  erkolcsi karpotlasra gondoltak, ismerve az orszag borzalmas penzugyi  helyzetet.  De mivel Horn mellett most Izrael Singer is penzt igert - a  dolgok mas iranyba fordultak naluk.  Ha igaza a hirek, ez a karterites  Hazanknak hatszazmilliard forintjaba fog kerulni,  ami, ha torvenybe  es kifizetesre kerul, meltan es joggal fog kivaltani antiszemitizmust.Arrol mar kar szolni, hogy a zsinagoga helyett inkabb a BAZILIKA-ba  ment volna el HORN GYULA es ott kert volna nyilvanosan bocsanatot  a kereszteny Magyarorszag sokat szenvedett es legalabb ket millio  aldozatot kitevo magyartol, akiket a kommunizmus pusztitott el,  amelynek o is aktiv es miniszteri hatalommal biro tagja volt.  De ezt  nem tette meg, mert tanacsadoitol nem ezt a parancsot kapta. Sot, a  romai Papanal tett latogatasanal sem kert bocsanatot a  kommunizmus bunei miatt, amit a keresztenseg ellen kovetett el a  kommunizmus.Visszaterve MONUS ARON nyilatkozatara, amiben semmi valotlan  nem volt, megis megerkezett a valasz ra a DEMOKRATA  szerkesztosegebe a svajci BERN-ben elo GOSZTONYI PETER  tortenesztol.  A kovetkezoket irta: "Nem kellene ezt a Monus Aron  nevezetu urat egy elmeszakertovel megvizsgaltatni?  Szerintem  egyenest hivna a mentoket, hogy az illetot a Lipotmezore vigyek.   Ennyi baromsag, amit ez az ur kinyilvanitott, predesztinalja ot a  gumicellaba".Vagyis a "tortenesz" ur nagyszeruen erzekelteti az altala hulyenek  nyilvanitott Monus Aron eltunteteset ugy, hogy az elmeszakerto  nyilvanitsa hulyenek es be vele a bolondok hazaba, ahol a  gumicellaban leelheti hatralevo eveit.Ugye, mennyire hasonlit ez arra, amikor a kommunistak mar  szuneteltettek az egyszeru tarkonlovest azokkal szemben, akik  "maskepp gondolkodtak", mint Lenin es Sztalin hu tanitvanyai? Eleg  volt az engedetlent behurcolni elmevizsgalatra, elmebetegnek  nyilvanitani es igy is eltunhetett nyomtalanul orokre.  Milyen jol  emlekszik a "tortenesz' erre es most, hogy ne tagadja meg onmagat,  ugyanezt a "gyogymodot" keri MONUS ARON eltuntetesere.Ami Gosztonyi Peter azon kitetelet illeti leveleben, hgoy "ennyi  baromsagot, amit ez az ur itt kinyilvanitott..."  legyen szabad  megjegyeznem, hogy GOSZTONYI PETER "tortenesz" volt az, aki sok  "baromsagot-marhasagot" irt eddigi mukodese folyaman, sot  olyanokat allitott, ami nem felelhet meg a valosagnak.Mivel az ujsagban megjeleno irasok ne legyenek tul hosszuak, hogy  masoknak szinten jusson hely megmondani azt, amit akarnak, jelen  esetben eltekintunk a tovabbi reszletezestol.Szerencsere azota a DEMOKRATA olvasoi is valaszoltak Gosztonyi  gusztustalan megjegyzesere Monus Aron ellen, es tobbek kozott  BOTOS JOZSEF azt irja: "Kar, hogy Gosztonlyi Peter nem tudja -  ervekkel szemben ellenervekkel, es nem ostoba, otromba  sertegetesekkel kell csatazni.  A stilusaval is van egy kis gondom.   Mintha mar hallottam volna valamit arrol, hogy a Szovjetunioban  hova kerultek a maskent gondolkodok.  Gosztonyi reakcioja  kisertetiesen analogiaja amannak."A masik leveliro, aki nevet nem fedi fel, azt valaszolja Gosztonyinak:  "On nagyon leertekeli otthoni kollegait.  Regen megvizsgaltattak  Monus urat elmeszakertovel, meg akkor, amikor a Nietzschhei  Birodalom cimu konyvet be akartak tiltani. A biro felolvasta a  szakvelemenyt, ami rendorsegen keszult (amikor ott fogva tartottak).  A vegen megkerdezte Monus ur: "azt irjak-e, hogy MEGVERTEK..?" De  ha ez Onnek keves lenne, Svajcban is megvizsgaltak.  On ennek a  bator, nagyon sok aldozatot vallalo tudosnak a munkajat  "baromsagnak" minositi, amikor Monus Aron a birosag elott  bizonyitotta igazsagat."Biztos vagyok benne, hogy  meg tobben megvedik nyilvanosan  Monus Aront Gosztonyi Peter "tortenesz" alaptalan piszkalodasa ellen. Csupan az a rejtely marad meg a leirtak utan, miert tette ezt  Gosztonyi Peter!?  Ahogy gondolom es biztosan tudom, sem Zoltai  Gusztav, sem Landeszmann rabbi, sem a magyar ellenallok es  antifasisztak szovetsege, sem Izrael Singer nem lelkesedik Monus  Aronert konyve elolvasasa utan, bizonyos elkotelezett faji-alap miatt.   Lehet, hogy ez az ok Gosztonyi Peter eseteben!?Revffy Laszlo  Anglia==Hazai dolgaink:  Seres Laszlo*:  KOZOSSEGI JOVATETEL  avagy miert nem megy, ami jar?  ["SZOMBAT", 1996. aprilis]Mire e sorok megjelennek, talan vegre megvan a dontes arrol, vegul  is ki alapit (koz)alapitvanyt a zsido kozossegi vagyon mukodtetesere;  talan vegre eldol, kikbol es kiknek a vezetese alatt mukodik  valamilyen kuratorium. Epp ideje volt mar rendbe tenni a dolgot, es  karteriteni kozossegunket a nacik/nyilasok altal elrabolt, a  sztalinistak altal allamositott vagyonert/mukincsert/ingatlanokert. A  fo kerdes -- es errol a Szombat tobbszor is beszamolt -- tovabbra is  az: helyreall-e vegre a magyar zsido szervezetek egysege, legalabb  annyira, hogy kepesek legyenek egy kuratoriumban egyuttmukodni.Egy nappal azelott, hogy ezt a cikket megirtam, interju jelent meg  Kozismert Politikussal, aki nem kis hucpevel kozolte: vegul is a zsidok  az okai az antiszemitizmusnak. (Nem igy mondta szo szerint, de ezt  sugallta.) Es mivel ok az okai, jobb lesz, ha nem kapatjak el magukat  karpotlasi koveteleseikkel, mert a tarsadalom nem szereti az ilyet,  kulonben is, az orszag gazdasagi lehetosegei. Nem, a nyilatkozat  ezuttal nem a hiers iro munkassaganak resze. Hanem a parlament  emberi jogi bizottsaganak elnoke, a szocialista parti GELLERT KIS  GABOR beszelt ilyen szellemben a Magyar Nemzetben. A zsidok  "onmersekletere" szolit fel annak a kormanynak a reprezentansa,  amely elodeit kovetve maig nem teljesitette a Parizsi Bekeszerzodest.  (Lapzartakor lemondtam arrol a szandekomrol, hogy Gellert Kisnek  elofizessem a Magyar Forumot. Vegye meg o.)DE HOGY IS VOLT EZ A KARPOTLAS-BIZNISZ?Azt hiszem, kezdetben vala Horn Gyula. Ez a mogorva kis ember ugy  ket eve megtette azt, amit masoknak mar regen meg kellett volna  tennie: a magyar nep neveben bocsanatot kert a holocaust miatt a  zsidosagtol es a ciganysagtol, elismerte az allam felelosseget, majd  New Yorkban Israel Singerrel targyalva igeretet tett a kozossegi  karpotlas rendezesere. Innentol kezdve porogtek fel az esemenyek,  es -- amennyire azt a kivulallo meg tudja itelni -- innentol elezodtek  ki a magyarorszagi zsido szervezetek regota huzodo belso ellentetei.Kozel egy honapig dolgoztam lapom, a Magyar Narancs szamara a  zsido karpotlas temajan. Napjaim azzal teltek, hogy zsido vezetokkel  es kulonbozo regi es uj sertettekkel talalkoztam. Mindenki mast  mondott, mindenki mast martott be es aztatott el, es csak abban az  egyben volt konszenzus, hogy mind megkerdezte: "Muszaj ezt  megirnia? Es eppen most?" (Es hat az is konszenzus volt, hogy a kozos  ellensegkep a teljes karteritesert kuzdo MUSZOE-s Schwarz Mihaly.  Ezt csak Schwarz bacsi latta maskepp.) Viszont ez a MOST eltart mar  egy ideje, es egyszer meg kellett mar irni, hogy a zsido szervezetek --  amelyek szerencsere semmivel sem kevesbe megosztottak, mint a  "magyarok"; szerencsere, mert ez is mutatja, hogy nem vagyunk  "jobbak", vagy kivalasztottak -- komoly LEGITIMACIOS VALSAGBAN  vannak, nem tudnak donteni egy kozos kuratorium aranyairol. Es ez  a konfliktus lenyege, nem az, hogy mi legyen a WJRO szerepe, vagy  hogy az allamtol visszakapott zsido vagyont szocialis celra, avagy  Telebingora koltsek.Onnon letuk bizonyitasaert harcolnak a magyar zsido szervezetek.  Paradox modon kulonosebb bazis nelkuli fantomletre kenyszerult a  magyar zsido kozelet (talan a hitelet kivetelevel). A Mazsihisz elerte,  hogy a kormannyal targyalhatott a tobbi zsido szervezet neveben is,  de ez a megbizas inkabb spiritualis, mint valos alapu: a zsido let  vallasi meghatarozottsaga ellentmond annak, hogy a nyolcvanezres  zsidosagnak csak toredeke jar zsinagogaba, csak kis reszuk fizet a  hitkozsegnek, a mai zsido fiatalok tobbsege pedig, ha meghallja a  "peszach" szot, legfeljebb azt mondja, hogy "egeszsegedre". Na most ez  a Mazsihisz, a legnagyobb szervezet. Akkor meg nem beszeltunk a  Mazsikerol, a Cionista Szovetsegrol vagy a B'nai B'rithrol, amelyeknel,  ugy tudom, ugyanazok az arcok rotalnak (rotalunk) "tagsag" cimen,  hogy kicsit egyszerubben fogalmazzak.A tet tehat az volt, vallasi vagy vilagi, fovarosi, vagy inkabb videki  celokat szolgaljon az EVI X-MILLIARD [kiemeles a Nemzet  szerkesztojetol] forintos (koz)alapitvany mukodese. Allandoan  visszatero aggodalomkent hallhattam ezen kivul munkam soran,  hogy a WJRO "ki akarja vinni a penzt" az orszagbol, azaz: tamogatni  akarja a nagy szamban kulfoldon (USA-ban, Izraelben) elo magyar  zsido csoportokat, szervezeteket. Amiben van igazsag: odakint  legalabb annyira realis a Parizsi Bekeszerzodes szellemenek  megfelelo "kozossegi elet", mint idehaza. Schwarz bacsi kerdesemre  mindenesetre kikerte maganak, hogy "egyes kulfoldi csoportok"  itthon feszultseget csinaljanak a penz reszbeni exportjaval. Aztan  derult ki: megsem visznek ki penzt.Beultem a hitkozseg legutobbi zartkoru kozgyulesere (ahol mellesleg  lemondattak a teljes vezetoseget(1)!), hogy megnezzem, hogyan  fogadjak a magyar zsidok Israel Singer WJRO-elnokot. Hosszas  meltatas, mersekelt taps, a szemekben a kerdes: mit akar maga? Az  onmagat lathatoan defenzivaban erzo Singer magyarazkodik es iger:  nem, nem visszuk ki a penzt az orszagbol, nem tudom, ki mondta  maguknak, de nem, elvegre a WJRO-vezetoknek mar van kocsijuk es  lakasuk. Singer persze demagog, hiszen senki nem allitotta, hogy  sajat celra koltenek a penzt. Hangjat felemelve kozli a magyar  zsidokkal: ok, a WJRO igenis nelkulozhetetlenek nemzetkozi szinten,  es akkor is segitenek, ha mi ezt nem akarjuk, es meg ott helyben uj  nemet penzeket iger. Hala, koszonet. Zoltai bejelenti, hogy ket napon  belul alairhato a (koz)alapitvany(2). Par nappal utana kapom a hirt,  ami egyik ujsagban sem jelenik meg: a kormany az iskolaepito  Lauderrel targyal, hogy o adjon penzt a (koz)alapitvanyba.A torvenyesen meghatarozott allami kotelessegvallalas ellenere tehat  megsem terhelodik az allami budzse? Az allam elintezi a zsido  onmersekletet a zsidok helyett, tekintettel az orszag valsagos  gazdasagi alapotara? Gellert Kis Gabor maganvelemenye a zsido  konszenzus resze? Talan az a legmegalazobb az egeszben, hogy ugy  nez ki: a veszekedo-marakodo magyar zsido szervezetek kozott csak  a kormany, meg persze az okos es gazdag amerikai zsidok tudnak  csak rendet rakni. A helyzet az, hogy mi, zsidok, iszonyuak tudunk  lenni.- (1) A vezetoseg menesztesere nem kerult sor. Lasd a Szombat  kozgyulesi beszamolojat a marciusi szamban (a szerk.) [Ezt a Nemzet  is kozolte.] (2) Az alapitvany [a "Szombat"] lapzartaig, marcius 11-ig  nem jott letre. [Azota a kormany mar hatarozott, letrejott!]==DEMOKRATA (21)Lovas Istvan:  MIERT LEGYENEK A ZSIDOK TULELOK?- kerdezi Michael Goldberg konzervativ rabbi, akinek konyve (Why  Should Jews Survive?) nemregiben jelent meg az Egyesult  Allamokban az Oxford kiadonal 191 oldalon, 23 dollaros aron.Amikor, irja a jo rabbi, Nathan Glazer 1957-ben megjelentette  klasszikussa valt tanulmanyat, az Amerikai Judaizmus c. konyvet,  egyetlen egyszer nem emlitette a holocaust szot. Akkoriban ugyanis  az amerikai zsido tudatbol a holocaust egyszeruen hianyzott es oda  csupan evekkel kesobb feszkelte be magat. (Magyarorszagon  lenyegesen kesobb, 1990 juniusa utan, egycsapasra - L.I.). Ami, idezi  Goldberg Glazert,  nagy meglepetes. Egy felmeres szerint 1991-re  mar az amerikai zsidok 85 szazaleka nyilatkozott ugy, hogy a  holocaust igen fontos zsido ontudatuk szempontjabol. Ez a  szazalekarany nagyobb, mint azoke, akik a toranak, Istennek, vagy  Izrael allamanak tulajdonitottak hasonlo fontossagot.Goldberg konyve ezzel a valtozassal foglalkozik. A korabban tobb  amerika i egyetemen vallast oktato rabbi jelenleg a los angelesi Bnai  Tikvah kongregacio szellemi vezetoje.Konyve legelso mondataban fogalmazza meg erveinek lenyeget: az  Isten nelkuli holocaust a zsido tulelest assa ala ahelyett, hogy azt  erositene. Megdobbento szavak. De Goldberg magyarazataban  konnyen elfogadhatova valik. Nezzuk tehat a magyarazatot.Szerinte minden vallasnak van egy fo tortenete, amely a vilag  megertesenek es az abban valo cselekves utmutatasanak modelje. A  judaizmusban ez a fo tortenet az exodus: Izrael gyermekei  szolgasagukbol Istenhez kialtanak es Isten, emlekezve Abrahammal,  Izsakkal es Jakobbal kotott egyezsegere, megszabaditja oket. Isten  Izrael felszabaditoja minden nemzedek szamara es Izrael az o  valasztott nepe.Goldberg szamara  ez a holocaust es a zsidokat idotlen idok ota ert  szenvedesek tanulsaga. A zsido nep tulelt minden tamadast a faraok  koratol Hitlerig, mert olyan Istenuk van, aki gondoskodik nepe  tuleleserol. Hogy miert teszi? Mert a zsidok a vilag megvaltasaban  kulcsszerepet jatszanak. A zsidok igazi celja, irja Goldberg rabbi, isten  nepekent szolgalni, akitol Isten vilaganak megvaltasa es Isten sajat  neve fugg. Mindaddig, ameddig a zsido nep a megallapodas ra eso  reszet teljesiti, Isten is teljesiti a szerzodes szerinti sajat  kotelezettseget.De, irja mergesen Goldberg, a zsidok mostanaban az Istenbe vetettt  hituket felcserelik a holocaust kultuszaval. E kultusz kettos eleme a  halal es a tuleles irant mutatott megszallottsag, es zsido szempontbol  mindketto problematikus. Kozossegek sora ruhaz be holocaust  muzeumokba es emlekmuvekbe, mikozben arcatlanul figyelmen  kivul hagyjak azt a zsido hagyomanyt, hogy a halottak siremlekeit  kerulni kell. De ennel sokkal rosszabb az, hogy a holocaust kultusz a  puszta fizikai tulelest hatarozta meg a zsido let celjakent.Goldberg szemeben ez illogikus: A zsidoknak nem szabad  ketelkedniuk abban, hogy tulelok lesznek - hacsak nem ketelkednek  abban, hogy Isten megtartja igereteit. Sot, allitja Goldberg, az ilyen  ketelyek az ateizmus egy formaja. A holocaustra es a fizikai tulelesre  helyezett hangsuly megvaltoztatja a judaizmus legalapvetobb  eloirasat es atirja legfontosabb imajat, a Shmat, amely  megparancsolja a zsidoknak, hogy szeressek Uratokat, Isteneteket  teljes szivetekkel, teljes lelketekkel es minden erotokkel. Ha a zsidok  e helyett csak a tulelest szeretik, akkor elutasitottak a megallapodast  Istennel es tulelesuk erdektelenne valik.==[Az IMF irtozatos bajban van - USA Kongresszusnak nem akarodzikfizetni az IMF-bulikat.  Az IMF azon a ponton van (mint a Szovjet-unio 1956 tajan), hogy egy nagyszabasu magyar "kamatrabszolgafelkeles" eseten le kell huznia a rolot.  Egy magyar adossagleiro akcionak pillanatnyilag hatalmas lehetosege van, mert a "penzugyi osszeomlast" az IMF mindenaron el akarja kerulni!]Dow Jones Business News -- May 24, 1996North Carolina Senator Seeks To Curb Outlay To IMF FacilityWASHINGTON -- North Carolina Senator Lauch Faircloth remains ''utterly opposed'' to additional U.S. contributions to an emergency cash facility for the International Monetary Fund (IMF), stressing he intends to work against added U.S. participation.Faircloth, who last year introduced legislation that would bar any budget authorization or appropriation toward further U.S. contributions to the General Arrangements to Borrow (GAB), underscored his determination to ''stop the formation of this bailout facility.'I would again stress that such a fund will present a moral hazard for countries to assume risk - and then assume they will be bailed out,'' the North Carolina Republican stated.Faircloth and Senate Banking Committee Chairman Alfonse D'Amato have raised concerns about the move to double the size of the existing GAB, which Treasury officials say will require budget authorization in fiscal 1998.The Treasury, which spearheaded negotiations that led Thursday to an accord in Paris among 23 of the world's wealthiest nations to bring the GAB to $49 billion, stresses than any use of the facility would be tied to 'strong' economic program conditionalities.Industrial nations moved last year to expand the GAB, which is a fund controlled by the donor countries and made available in times of cash pinches to the IMF, after the IMF was required to put up a record $17.8 billion credit to help stabilize Mexico in the wake of its peso crisis.The IMF is also seeking to double its share capital over the next year, something would also require the budget request from Congress, which recently hasn't been inclined to fully meet U.S. cash commitments to the IMF or other multilateral financial institutions.==OMRI: RUSSIAN ELECTION SURVEYWHY DOES ZYUGANOV'S ELECTION PLATFORM DIFFER FROM HIS PARTY'S PROGRAM? Complaining of a hysterical "anti-communist cacophony" aimed at discrediting Gennadii Zyuganov, the pro-communist newspaper Pravda on 18 May explained why the campaign platform Zyuganov issued in March differs from the program the Communist Party (KPRF) approved in January 1995. (In particular, the 1995 program called for widespread renationalization.) Pravda argued that the KPRF is merely the strongest among scores of groups in Zyuganov's bloc of "popular-patriotic forces" and could not impose its program on the entire coalition. Second, an election platform should be oriented toward the mood of the majority of working people, not all of whom support socialism--just as, the paper argued, the 1918 decree on land redistribution differed markedly from the Bolshevik program. Furthermore, a party program has a different "horizon" from an election platform, which is only meant to outline policy over the next four years. Most of the election platform was published in Sovetskaya Rossiya on 19 March, but Zyuganov has delayed releasing his economic platform several times, reportedly due to disagreements within the KPRF. It is now scheduled to be revealed on 25 May, and it will no doubt strike a more moderate note than the January 1995 KPRF program, so as to appeal to voters who dislike President Boris Yeltsin's policies but might fear the consequences of renationalization. -- Laura BelinFEDOROV PLEDGES TO VOTE AGAINST YELTSIN AND ZYUGANOV . . . Presumably seeking to dispel rumors that he will withdraw from the campaign before 16 June or throw his support behind President Yeltsin before the second round of voting, Svyatoslav Fedorov announced that if the runoff pits Yeltsin against Gennadii Zyuganov, he will vote against both candidates, Radio Mayak reported on 18 May. Fedorov said he wants to wait for the appearance of "a leader capable of building a society of popular socialism in Russia." Opinion polls put support for Fedorov in the single digits, far short of what he would need to qualify for the runoff himself. Last week, he called for a new coalition government to be formed, including all major political parties and social groups. However, campaigning in Irkutsk on 21 May, Fedorov said he was not interested in the post of prime minister, according to ITAR-TASS. -- Laura Belin---BUT HIS FORMER NUMBER TWO IS BACKING YELTSIN. Aleksei Kazannik, who ran unsuccessfully for the State Duma last year as the number two candidate for Fedorov's Party of Workers' Self-Government, emphatically supported Yeltsin during the president's recent campaign swing through Kazannik's native region of Omsk. Kazannik first gained prominence in May 1989, when, as a member of the USSR Congress of People's Deputies, he was elected to the Supreme Soviet but gave up his seat to Yeltsin. On 5 October 1993, one day after troops loyal to Yeltsin shelled the parliament into submission, Kazannik was appointed procurator-general. However, he resigned just five months later, objecting to pressure from Yeltsin to ignore an amnesty the Duma had granted to the October 1993 parliamentary ringleaders and the main conspirators in the August 1991 coup. Kazannik was subsequently critical of Yeltsin's authoritarian tendencies. Nevertheless, he told Russian TV (RTR) on 18 May that he holds nothing personal against the president, who he said will continue pro-reform policies: "I will do everything I can to encourage as many voters as possible in Omsk Oblast to vote for him." -- Laura BelinYAVLINSKII FLYER STRESSES LESSER-KNOWN ASPECTS OF HIS BIOGRAPHY. Yabloko leader Grigorii Yavlinskii initially became well-known as the author of the 500-Day Plan, a 1990 blueprint for the rapid establishment of a market economy in the Soviet Union, but his campaign literature does not mention that aspect of his biography. Instead, flyers distributed in Moscow describe his early jobs, including work as a mail carrier, and accomplishments such as winning the Ukrainian junior boxing championship in 1968. Between 1976 and 1984, he worked in the USSR Coal Industry Ministry, visiting many of the country's mines and miraculously a pit flood. His knowledge of the economy from the bottom up helped him design a plan of gradual transition, the flyer claims. The pamphlet portrays Yavlinskii as the candidate most likely to improve Russian cooperation with the other former Soviet republics. The back of the brochure carries endorsements from several leading democrats, including Yelena Bonner and Sergei Kovalev, who argue that Yavlinskii is more likely than Yeltsin to prevent a communist return if he can gain the support of the other democratic groups--an extremely unlikely scenario. -- Robert Orttung in MoscowLEBED FLYER STRESSES TRUTH AND ORDER. Aleksandr Lebed's colorful flyers, printed on high-quality, glossy paper, show the candidate in civilian clothes, smiling, and with his wife, a stark contrast to the military image he presented during the Duma campaign, when he was a leader of the Congress of Russian Communities. Lebed promises to impose order on the state by getting rid of the bureaucrats who call themselves "democrats in the morning, communists at lunch, and patriots in the evening." He also plans to free the economy of officials who, he argues, see the reforms merely as a chance to make a profit. His economic program consists of giving the economy over to millions of small property holders while reducing taxes and increasing freedom for entrepreneurs. The retired lieutenant general promises to restore order to the country's cities and villages by reminding the police that their job is to destroy the bandits. The flyer also includes some of Lebed's more striking slogans, such as "There really should have been only one unit fighting in Chechnya: a unit composed of the sons of the Kremlin leaders," and "Weak people conduct wars. The strong don't allow them to happen." -- Robert Orttung in MoscowZHIRINOVSKY ON CHECHNYA CONFLICT SETTLEMENT . . . Speaking on the Russian Public TV (ORT) show Odin na odin (One on One) on 16 May, Liberal Democratic Party of Russia leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky outlined his plan for solving the Chechen crisis. He said that the war can only be ended if Chechen fighters are deported to Turkey, Jordan, or Azerbaijan, after having being dosed with narcotics. He suggested that rival presidential candidate and pharmaceutical magnate Vladimir Bryntsalov, who was the second participant in the ORT program, could provide the drugs. Zhirinovsky also predicted that Chechen militants will carry out terrorist acts before 16 June in North Ossetiya and Stavropol Krai, which border Chechnya. -- Anna Paretskaya---AND AS SEEN BY HIS WIFE. Zhirinovsky's wife of more than 25 years, Galina Lebedeva, described her husband's private side on NTV's Itogi on 19 May. She declared that her husband, who is notorious for his scandalous public behavior, is "very calm and well-balanced" at home; "he behaves so quietly that you barely hear and see him, and he always has a book with him." Lebedeva said that her husband has read everything ever written by Marx, Engels, and Lenin. She added that politics is the main passion of his life, the only thing that ever makes her jealous, and that he also enjoys swimming, playing soccer, and going to the ballet and opera. Lebedeva praised her husband's healthy lifestyle, saying he is a nonsmoker and the most he drinks is a drop of champagne and mineral water. -- Anna ParetskayaGORBACHEV NOT WELCOMED IN HOME REGION . . . Former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev was given the cold shoulder in his native region of Stavropol Krai, AFP reported on 17 May. In Stavropol, the city where he served as first secretary of the Communist Party regional committee for eight years, the krai Governor Petr Marchenko refused to meet with him, and only one small private local TV station offered him airtime. Furthermore, university students at his alma mater rejected his request to meet with them because they did not want their school "politicized." In the village where Gorbachev spent his childhood, he was welcomed only by a small group of Western journalists; even his old friends and neighbors expressed surprise and contempt for his participation in the presidential race, according to The New York Times. Opinion polls register Gorbachev's support at 1% to 2%. -- Anna Paretskaya---BUT CLAIMS COMMUNISTS OFFERED HIM COALITION. During a free slot on Radio Mayak on 17 May, Mikhail Gorbachev claimed that on his campaign trips, regional Communist Party (KPRF) officials have repeatedly approached him and offered to help him forge a coalition with KPRF leader Gennadii Zyuganov. While he did not object to Zyuganov personally, Gorbachev said such negotiations were out of the question because Zyuganov's associates, including Anatolii Lukyanov, Valentin Varennikov, Albert Makashov, and Vasilii Starodubtsev, helped plan the August 1991 coup, which he said caused the collapse of the USSR. (KPRF figures generally blame Gorbachev for the breakup of the USSR; at campaign rallies, Zyuganov has been known to refer to Gorbachev derisively as "the one with the patch on his head.") Gorbachev repeated that he hopes a "third force" will materialize and his "young partners" Grigorii Yavlinskii, Aleksandr Lebed, and Svyatoslav Fedorov might withdraw from the race in his favor, since he is the most experienced candidate. On 16 May, Lebed said Gorbachev "has wanted very much to become my daddy, but I have preferred to remain an orphan," ORT reported. -- Anna ParetskayaMILLIONAIRE BRYNTSALOV STRESSES SOCIALIST GOALS IN APPEAL TO VOTERS. In a 10 minute free advertisement on ORT on 20 May, pharmaceutical magnate Vladimir Bryntsalov stressed the socialist nature of his program. The advertisement shows Bryntsalov, the chairman of the just-formed Russian Socialist Party, on the street making speeches and scenes from the high- tech factory floor of his company Ferane. It also shows the interior of his very plush office, replete with pictures of the patriarch of the Orthodox Church, Aleksii II, and other religious symbols. His campaign slogan is "Bryntsalov: the Best Medicine for Russia." In his presentation, Bryntsalov claimed that he could raise the minimum wage from its current level of 75,000 rubles ($15) to 3.5 million rubles ($700) and raise the minimum pension to 3 million rubles ($600). Bryntsalov also called for wage leveling, so that a minister, for example, would receive only three or four times as much as his subordinates. Bryntsalov's socialist government would protect the right to buy and sell private property on land but also guarantee that capitalists do not "steal" people's work. He advocates capitalist methods as the most effective means of production but would ensure that workers are well paid and allowed to keep the benefits of their labor. However, RIA-Novosti reported on 14 May that workers at Bryntsalov's enterprises are allegedly forced to join his new political party in order to keep their jobs. -- Robert Orttung in MoscowBALLOT WILL NOT SHOW MOST CANDIDATES' PARTY AFFILIATIONS. The Central Electoral Commission (TsIK) has ruled that presidential candidates' party affiliations will be mentioned on the ballot voters see on 16 Juneonly if a specific political organization nominated them and collected signatures for their presidential bids. (Most of the candidates technically were nominated by citizens' "initiative groups" rather than registered political parties.) Other candidates are free to choose whether to specify any political affiliations, Radio Rossii reported on 16 May. So far, only Yabloko leader Grigorii Yavlinskii and Liberal Democratic Party of Russia head Vladimir Zhirinovsky have requested that the names of their parties appear on the ballot. Gennadii Zyuganov will be identified not as the leader of the Communist Party but rather as the representative of the "popular-patriotic bloc." President Yeltsin does not belong to any political party. -- Anna ParetskayaMEDIARYABOV: SOME CANDIDATES ARE BREAKING THE RULES. According to Central Electoral Commission Chairman Nikolai Ryabov, some presidential candidates are violating the rules on campaign agitation, RTR reported on 18 May. In particular, he cited materials supporting Gennadii Zyuganov that incited "social hatred," such as an April interview in Zavtra during which Zyuganov called television "our main enemy today." By contrast, Ryabov said the same day that the extensive media coverage being given to President Yeltsin is fair because the law does not make clear "where the actions of the president end" and those of the candidate begin, Reuters reported. Appearing before the State Duma on 17 May, Ryabov said the anti-Communist glossy newspaper Ne dai bog (God forbid), which has appeared in voters' mailboxes across Russia, also violates the rules, ITAR-TASS reported. For instance, the name of the paper's founder (uchreditel) does not appear anywhere on the publication. -- Laura BelinCANDIDATES DISCUSS ATTITUDES TOWARD TV. The 18 May edition of Nezavisimaya gazeta asked presidential candidates what actions they would take concerning television if elected. Gennadii Zyuganov said he hoped the "best representatives of the creative intelligentsia" could help alleviate the "unrestrained and sometimes cynical transition from romantic television to commercial television." Vladimir Zhirinovsky, who in the past has threatened to shut down NTV and other independent media, claimed that he would not take a single program off the air if elected. Instead, he would show "more honest" programs to compete against slanderous ones: "word against word, truth against lies." Aleksandr Lebed said Channel 1 should remain in state hands (49% of the shares in the Channel 1 broadcaster ORT were sold to private firms under a controversial November 1994 presidential decree). Mikhail Gorbachev, whose policy of glasnost changed Soviet television forever, said television should reflect genuine freedom of speech, unlike its current position as the "political theater of one actor, where stormy applause leading to an ovation is constantly heard." President Yeltsin--who is currently the main beneficiary of biased television coverage--quite understandably declined to answer the paper's questions, Nezavisimaya gazeta observed. -- Laura BelinYELTSIN ADS MOST VISIBLE IN MOSCOW AND ON TV. President Yeltsin is by far the most visible presidential candidate in Moscow. He has plastered the city with billboards that show him shaking hands with Moscow Mayor Yurii Luzkhov, who is also running for re-election on 16 June. The two tower over the Kremlin churches with the slogan "Muscovites have already made their choice in 96." On television, Yeltsin is running an upbeat paid advertisement for a rock concert that is touring the country as part of the "Vote or You Lose" campaign aimed at mobilizing young people. The ad shows a number of pop groups with the slogan "Yeltsin-- Our President." The incumbent is also playing the anti-communist card with a number of testimonials from average people describing how difficult life was under the old regime. One paid advertisement on NTV gives the autobiography of a worker from Yaroslavl who claims that if the communists come back, people will be forced to use rationing coupons as in the late 1980s and early 1990s, while the comrades will eat in well-stocked cafeterias. The advertisement ends with Yeltsin's signature under the words "I believe, I love, I hope." In a newspaper advertisement printed in the 21 May issue of Izvestiya, a woman describes how it was impossible to earn more than the average salary by working hard during the Brezhnev era. Yeltsin used a similar format in his 21 May free airtime slot on ORT. Well-known figures, such as Forward, Russia! leader Boris Fedorov, described the dire consequences of a communist return to power, but Yeltsin did not appear once in the 10 minute presentation. -- Robert Orttung in MoscowZYUGANOV'S CAMPAIGN TO SUE NEWSPAPER. Gennadii Zyuganov's campaign headquarters are planning to sue Komsomolskaya pravda for publishing a document on 15 May that it claimed was a secret Communist Party (KPRF) economic program, according to the 17 May Kommersant-Daily. Zyuganov has vehemently denied that his party has a secret extremist agenda, and KPRF figures have denounced the publication as a "falsehood." The anti- communist press has played up rumors of a secret program ever since KPRF Duma member Valentin Varennikov claimed on 16 March that the party has an unpublished "maximum plan." Varennikov meant to defend Zyuganov against charges leveled by more orthodox communists that he was too moderate. Kommersant-Daily also reported that a controversial interview with Zyuganov published in the Far East newspaper Amurskaya pravda contained inaccuracies. Zyuganov was quoted as saying that he would not take orders from "odious" members of the KPRF leadership including Varennikov, the party's deputy chairman Valentin Kuptsov, or Albert Makashov, one of the leaders of the opposition to Yeltsin during October 1993 street clashes. Apparently someone at Amurskaya pravda added the word "odious" to the text, Kommersant-Daily reported. -- Laura BelinOFFICIAL MEDIA ACCUSED OF "BRAINWASHING" RUSSIANS. Figures in Yeltsin's circle are using the media to carry out "unprecedented" levels of "brainwashing," according to the latest edition of the nationalist and pro-Zyuganov newspaper Zavtra (no. 20). The paper said that when covering Yeltsin's campaign appearances, news programs use photo montage or commentary to distort the true nature of the events: "Not even one- hundredth of what actually takes place during Yeltsin's tours of the regions finds its way to the television screen." Curiously, for a newspaper that frequently attributes Russia's ills to "foreign secret services," Zavtra complained that "in any Western society," hidden advertisements such as those in favor of Yeltsin on the Channel 1 broadcaster ORT "would long ago have become a matter of legal proceedings." -- Laura BelinORT MANAGERS DISCUSS CHANNEL 1 COVERAGE. The Moscow-based media are generally biased toward President Yeltsin, probably none more so than the Channel 1 broadcaster ORT, informally known as "the president's television." In an interview published in Argumenty i fakty (no. 16), ORT's General Director Sergei Blagovolin admitted that he personally supports the current authorities but said opposition figures receive airtime on his network as well. When asked why Yeltsin is given so much more exposure on news programs than other candidates, Blagovolin said the president leads an "active political life." The most powerful figure at ORT is arguably Logovaz head Boris Berezovskii, who is technically the deputy chairman of ORT's board of directors but who is considered to have more influence over the network's policy than the chairman of the board, Aleksandr Yakovlev. In an interview published in the most recent Moskovskie novosti, Berezovskii admitted that his investment in ORT was not entirely "altruistic" and the network's election coverage was not "neutral" but said ORT supports a "compromise" between different political forces in Russia. Berezovskii was one of the 13 entrepreneurs who signed an appeal in late April for a political compromise to avert civil war. He is also a primary financial backer of Nezavisimaya gazeta and the popular magazine Ogonek. -- Laura BelinANALYSIS AND PREDICTIONSLATEST OPINION POLLS SHOW GAINS FOR YELTSIN. For the first time since President Yeltsin declared his bid for re-election, most opinion polls show him in the lead. For instance, a poll by the Institute for Comparative Social Research showed him with an 8.4% lead over the previous front-runner, Gennadii Zyuganov, Reuters reported on 18 May. According to that survey, Yeltsin's probable support in first-round voting has grown from 20.7% to 27.7% over the last month, while Zyuganov's support has dropped to 19.3% in May against 19.8% in April. The latest ROMIR-Gallup agency poll shows Yeltsin with 32% and Zyuganov with 25%, NTV reported. Public Opinion Foundation and VCIOM polls give Yeltsin smaller leads of 4% and 1%, respectively, according to NTV and Segodnya. The latest poll conducted by the Institute of Sociology of Parliamentarism bucked the trend, measuring Zyuganov support at 42% compared to 27% for Yeltsin, Reuters reported on 17 May. But even the director of that institute told Moskovskii komsomolets on 21 May that Yeltsin's campaign is gaining momentum. Polls in Russia are often misleading, since people are afraid to reveal their true preferences to pollsters assumed to sympathize with the authorities. -- Anna ParetskayaRUSSIA'S POLITICAL DIVISION IS MORE URBAN-RURAL THAN TERRITORIAL. In recent years, some analysts have discerned a north-south political division of Russia, with more support for reform above the 55th parallel and a pro-Communist "red belt" in the south. However, Presidential Council member Leonid Smirnyagin claimed that the political differences between urban and rural areas in Russia are much stronger than those separating regions. In an article written for the 22 May edition of Politicheskaya sreda, a supplement to the official newspaper Rossiiskie vesti, Smirnyagin argued that although the general notion of a north- south political divide is legitimate, each region is politically diverse: the larger the city, town, or village, the stronger its support for reforms. He argued that lately the main regional cities have been more influenced by the areas surrounding them than by Moscow and St. Petersburg. According to Smirnyagin, about 10% of Russian voters live in the Moscow and St. Petersburg areas, and about the same number live in purely rural areas. About a quarter of voters live in regional capital cities, another 25% in smaller towns; others live in "transitional" areas. -- Anna ParetskayaThis material was reprinted with permission of the Open Media     Research Institute, a nonprofit organization with research offices in     Prague, Czech Republic. For more information on OMRI publications,     please write to:  info@omri.cz
