<title>Nemzet 1996.06.15</title><BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000"><h1>Nemzet 1996.06.15</h1><!-- body="start" --><pre>N     N  EEEEEEE  M     M  ZZZZZZZ  EEEEEEE  TTTTTTTNN    N  E        MM   MM       Z   E           TN N   N  E        M M M M      Z    E           TN  N  N  EEEE     M  M  M     Z     EEEE        TN   N N  E        M     M    Z      E           TN    NN  E        M     M   Z       E           TN     N  EEEEEEE  M     M  ZZZZZZZ  EEEEEEE     T--->> M A G Y A R   I N T E R N E T   V I L A G L A P <<---</pre>==Lovas Istvan: <br>[Demokrata]<br><br>AZ USA AZ ERDELYI MAGYAROK ELLEN -  <br>LANTOSNAK "MAGYARPROBLEMAJA VAN"?<br><br>Mire lapunk e heti szama megjelenik, az amerikai kongresszus ill. <br>szenatus illetekes bizottsagai a terveknek megfeleloen esetleg mar <br>dontest hoztak  arrol, hogy a Romaniaban elo magyar kisebbseg <br>utolso "fegyveret" is kicsavarjak-e keze kozul. Ha a mult a <br>zsinormertek, akkor minden bizonnyal kicsavarjak.<br><br>Jelenleg az Egyesult Allamok a legnagyobb kereskedelmi <br>kedvezmenyt nyujtja Romanianak ugy, hogy annak <br>meghosszabbitasat  evente felulvizsgaljak. Az 1974-ben hozott, un. <br>Jackson-Vanik torvenymodositas ugyanis kimondja, hogy a "Most <br>Favored Nation"-nek (MFN) nevezett vamkedvezmeny (amely <br>gyakorlatilag azt jelenti, hogy a kedvezmenyezett normalis <br>vamtarifaval exportalhat az Egyesult Allamokba) megvonhato azoktol <br>az allamoktol, amelyekben nem tartjak tiszteletben az emberi <br>jogokat.  Az amerikai kulugyminiszterium mar hosszabb ideje rossz <br>szemmel nezi azt a "megalazo torturat", amelyen Romanianak kell <br>evente keresztulmennie, amikor megvizsgaljak, vajon az Iliescu-<br>kormany eleget tesz-e az 1974-es Kereskedelmi Torveny IV-ik <br>fejezeteben rogzitett felteteleknek. Magukat megnevezni nem kivano <br>amerikai megfigyelok szerint az amerikai kulugyminiszterium most <br>Phil Crane Illinois allambeli kongresszusi kepviselot kerte fel arra, <br>terjessze be a Hazba azt a 3161-es szamot kapott kongresszusi <br>hatarozatot, mely szerint Romania vegervenyesen megkapna a <br>legnagyobb vamkedvezmenyt es a Colorado allambeli Hank Brown <br>szenatort, hogy egy hasonlo javaslatot (1644-es javaslat) a <br>szenatusban nyujtson be. Phil Crane es Hank Brown hatarozati <br>javaslataval egeszen majus 3-ig egyedul maradt, amikor is Tom <br>Lantos, kaliforniai demokrataparti kepviselo (akit 1994 utan a <br>Magyar Televizioban tobb alkalommal tevesen "szenatornak" <br>neveztek) bejelentette: o is tamogatja az "MFN" eves <br>felulvizsgalatanak megszunteteset Romania eseteben. A <br>kulugyminiszterium hivatalosan is tamogatja a beterjesztest.<br><br>Az esetrol - mint varhato volt - a Horn-kormany <br>mediaintezmenyeinek - es a Horn-kormanyt tamogato magancegek - <br>tudositoi (vagyis az osszes, Amerikaban allomasozo tudosito) egy szot <br>sem jelentettek.  A mintegy masfel millio magyar szarmazasu <br>amerikai szavazot kepviselo "Magyar Lobby" levelkampanyba <br>kezdett, hogy meggyozzek kongresszusi kepviseloiket, szavazzanak a <br>beterjesztett hatarozati javaslat ellen. A Magyar Lobby mindenek <br>elott azt koveteli, hogy a vamkedvezmenyt a magyar etnikai <br>kozosseg kulturalis autonomiajahoz, a magyar egyhazi es iskolai <br>tulajdon visszaadasahoz (beleertve a Bolyai egyetemet), az <br>oktatasban es a kozigazgatasban a magyar nyelv hasznalatahoz, az <br>Europai Unio 12O1-es ajanlasanak alkalmazasahoz,  es a <br>kirakatperben, igazsagtalanul elitelt Cseresznyes Palnak adando <br>amnesztiahoz kosse.  A Magyar Lobby  tagjai Bob Dole szenatornak is <br>kuldtek levelet, amelyben a republikanusok valoszinu <br>elnokjeloltjenek felhivjak a figyelmet arra, hogy az 1947. februar 1O-<br>en alairt Parizsi Bekeszerzodes ertelmeben az Egyesult Allamok es a <br>tobbi szerzodo nagyhatalom felelos a Magyarorszag teruleten kivul <br>elo magyar etnikai kozossegek jogainak betartatasaert. A Magyar <br>Lobby tagjai a Koltsegvetesi Bizottsag elnokenek irt hasonlo <br>tiltakozasukban azt is megemlitettek, hogy az amerikai hatarozatot <br>kulonosen veszelyes most meghozni, ugyanis azt az Iliescu-kormany <br>a romaniai valasztasok elott ugy ertelmezheti, hogy a kedvezo <br>washingtoni dontes tamogatast jelent jelenlegi politikajahoz. Liptak <br>Bela, a tiltakozasi kampany fo szervezoje, surgette a Magyar Lobby <br>tagjait, hogy Clinton elnoknek irando levelukben hangsulyozzak: a <br>Trianonban alairt Kisebbsegvedelmi Szerzodes Magyarorszag <br>szomszedainak kotelessegeve tette, hogy a magyar kozossegek <br>szamara visszaadjak az iskolakat es egyhazi tulajdont, a magyar <br>nyelv hasznalatat garantaljak, valamint hogy tiszteletben tartsak a  <br>magyar kisebbseg kulturalis es kozigazgatasi autonomiajat. Liptak  a <br>Magyar Lobby tagjainak az Interneten eljuttatott leveleben <br>megjegyzi, hogy a szenatus albizottsaganak az ugyben tartott <br>meghallgatasan a washingtoni magyar nagykovetseg reszerol senki <br>sem volt jelen, ami, tegyuk hozza - tekintettel egy, az udvarias stilust <br>az orszag erdekeivel lehangolo gyakorisaggal osszekevero,  volt <br>kommunista kulugyminiszter es egy SZDSZ-es, minden eredeti <br>otletnek fajoan hijan levo allamtitkar altal vezetett diplomaciai <br>gepezetre - az ellenkezojevel okozott volna meglepetest. <br><br>Tom Lantos viselkedese az ugyben meglehetosen figyelemre melto. <br>Legalabb ket szempontbol. Az egyik Lantos kovetkezetes <br>romanbaratsaga, a masik pedig a fasiszta jelensegek eliteleseben <br>mutatkozo ellentmondasossaga. De kezdjuk az utobbival. Mint <br>emlekezetes, Tom Lantos volt az, aki az ismert Csurka-kijelentes <br>(New York-Parizs-Tel-Aviv-Budapest vonal) kapcsan 1992. <br>szeptember 23-an sajat rendezeseben lepett fel az amerikai <br>kepviselohazban. Ugyanakkor most annak a rezsimnek siet a <br>segitsegere, amely tobb emlekmuvet keszittetett Antonescu, a <br>fasiszta diktator emlekere, a legszelsosegesebb, Hitlert megszegyenito <br>antiszemita traktatumoknak nyujt alig titkolt segitseget es amely <br>igen jo viszonyt tart fenn a szelsosegen nacionalista Funar, kolozsvari <br>polgarmesterrel. Ami mutatja, hogy Lantos vagy a Csurka-ugyben <br>nem volt oszinte, vagy most nem. A jelek viszont erosen arra utalnak, <br>hogy  Lantosnak a romanbaratsag fontosabb az antiszemitizmus <br>elleni harcnal. Nezzuk, miert, vagyis Lantos "tortenelmi" <br>romanbaratsagat.  Tom Lantost mar Ceausescu idejen is igazi <br>romanbaratkent ismertek a beavatottak. Fokent az akkori bukaresti <br>nagykovet, David Funderburk, aki tapasztalatairol konyvet is irt (es <br>amelynek kiadasi jogat 1990 elejen egy SZDSZ-iranyitas alatt allo <br>konyvkiado vette meg potom penzert "szegenysegere" hivatkozva. A <br>konyvet a mai napig nem adta ki). <br><br>Funderburk nagykovet munkajanak alaphangjat legjobban talan <br>konyve legelso mondata jellemzi: "Az amerikai kulugyminiszterium <br>es a kommunista rendszerek mar joideje egyuttmukodnek."  Az <br>egyebkent politologus es jelenleg kongresszusi kepviselo nagykovet <br>igy irja le  Tom Lantos kepviselo romaniai latogatasat: ""1981 vege es <br>1985 nyara kozott a ket legfontosabb kongresszusi kuldottseget Tom <br>Lantos es Sam Gibbons kepviselok vezettek.  A Politics in America <br>szerint a kaliforniai demokrataparti Tom Lantos, aki Budapesten, <br>Magyarorszagon szuletett zsido szulok gyermekekent, kemeny <br>antikommunista hireben allt. 1983. januari, Romaniaban tett <br>latogatasat kovetoen elgondolkoztam, hogy mi lehet az alapja <br>antikommunista hirnevenek. A Lantos delegacioban Don Bonker es <br>William Frenzel kepviselok is reszt vettek feleseguk kisereteben, es <br>veluk utazott Powell Moore a kongresszusi kapcsolatokert felelos <br>allamtitkar.  1983. januar 19-i naplobejegyzesem szerint a kuldottseg <br>gyalazatos teljesitmenyt nyujtott, ami alaasta azt az amerikai <br>erofeszitest, hogy a ketoldalu kapcsolatokban a kolcsonosseg elve <br>uralkodjon... A valsag kozepette a csoport latogatasanak a lenyege az <br>volt, hogy megerositse a roman kormanyt abban, ne aggodjon, amiert <br>a Jackson-Vanik torvenymodositast, a legnagyobb kereskedelmi <br>kedvezmeny elvet es a helsinki vallalasokat a  legsulyosabb modon <br>megserti. Hihetetlen, de Anette Lantos azt mondta, hogy a fentiek <br>megserteset torvenybe iktato bukaresti kormanyrendelet szerinte <br>torvenyes es jogos. Azt is elmondta, hogy Romania es Bukarest <br>gyonyoru - a kocsiablakbol latta - es feltetlenul ujra felkeresi majd <br>az orszagot, amely egyik kedvenc helye. Lantos kepviselo azt mondta, <br>ha felajanlanak, hogy valasszon nagykoveti allast Brusszel vagy <br>Bukarest kozott, akkor Bukarestet valasztana.  Nem kellett azonban <br>Romaniaban elniuk es latniuk, hogy milyen mertekben szenved a <br>lakossag.  Ceausescu kulonosen ertett ahhoz, hogy  sajat magukat <br>nagyon fontosaknak kepzelo embereket manipulaljon. Marpedig az <br>amerikai legiero repulogepenek szemelyzete szerint Lantosnal  magat <br>fontosabbnak kepzelo ember meg nem lepett gepuk fedelzetere.  A <br>Lantos-kuldottseg legfontosabb talalkozoja januar 19-ere esett, <br>amikor Ceausescu ket orara fogadta.  Ceausescu a szokasos trukkjet <br>vette be: "nektek nagyobb szuksegtek van ram, mint nekem ratok, <br>igy tehat ha kell, egyedul haladok az uton", ami  vendegeit vedekezo <br>allasba kenyszeritette. Ceausescu elmondta, hogy Romania megvolt a <br>legnagyobb kereskedelmi elv nelkul korabban is es ha szukseges, <br>majd ismet csak elboldogul nelkule.  Azt allitotta, semmifele feltetelt <br>nem fogadna el azert, hogy megtartsa a legnagyobb kedvezmenyt.  <br>Azzal ervelt, hogy az Egyesult Allamok Romanianal tobbet veszitene, <br>ha a legnagyobb kereskedelmi kedvezmenyt elvennek orszagatol. <br>Igyekezett igazolni a kivandorlokra vetett oktatasi illeteket es azt, <br>hogy a kivandorlas fenntartasa nem kepezi az amerikai-roman <br>kereskedelmi egyezmeny reszet... Lantos hangsulyozta Ceausescunak <br>a nemzetkozi teruleten mutatott nagy bolcsesseget es <br>vezetokepesseget, fokent a leszerelest es a beket illetoen. Dicserte <br>Romania ugynevezett fuggetlen kulpolitikajat... Lantos volt az osszes, <br>Romaniaba latogato kuldottsegek kozul gyakorlatilag az egyetlen, aki <br>kifejezte remenyet, hogy Romania tobb evre megkapja a legnagyobb <br>kereskedelmi kedvezmeny elvet es hogy az evente esedekes <br>felulvizsgalat terhe alol mentesiteni fogjak. Lantos hangsulyozta, <br>hogy a magyarokkal nem bannak rosszabbul a romanoknal, es hogy a <br>magyarok kulturalis nepirtast emlegeto panasza alaptalan. Lantosek <br>csodalkozasukat fejeztek ki, hogy magyar szarmazasukkal <br>kapcsolatban semmifele rosszallast sem hallottak. Mindehhez meg <br>Lantos hozzatette: ha 1984-ben demokrataparti elnokot valasztanak, <br>rabirja majd arra, hogy a kovetkezo evben meglatogassa Romaniat. A <br>kuldottseg tobbi tagja elmondta nekem, hogy meglepodtek Lantosnak <br>Ceausescu iranti, elkepeszto merteku tiszteleten, es hogy Lantos <br>altalaban kemenyebb szokott lenni ilyen alkalmakkor... Amikor <br>roman tisztsegviselokkel talalkozott, mindig megdicserte Romania <br>fuggetlen kulpolitikajat (mint emlekezetes, a "beketabor" orszagai <br>kozul peldaul ebben az idoben csak Ceausescu tartott fenn egyedul <br>diplomaciai kapcsolatokat Izraellel - A szerk.). A talalkozok elott es <br>utan ugyanakkor bevallotta, hogy Romania kulpolitikaja nem is <br>annyira fuggetlen. A talalkozok idejen Lantos soha egyetlen szot sem <br>szolt az emberi jogokrol. Holott ezek a talalkozok jelentettek azt az <br>alkalmat, amikor segiteni tudta volna azon ezreket, akiket <br>bebortonoztek, uldoztek es nem engedtek kivandorolni. A <br>talalkozokat kovetoen Lantosne atadott nekem egy jegyzeket, amely <br>kivandorolni szandekozo csaladokat tartalmazott es azt mondta <br>felesegemnek, hogy Washingtonban egyik fontos feladatanak tekinti, <br>hogy harom roman csaladnak sikeruljon elhagynia az orszagot, mivel <br>e csaladok rokonai gyakran latogatjak meg irodajat.  Lantosek <br>bukaresti szereplese azonban sokkal nehezebbe tette a harom csalad <br>emigralasat.  Lantos Washingtonba visszaterte utan az elso volt, aki <br>politikailag reklamozta az utja alatt elert eredmenyeket es az altala <br>mutatott gondoskodast."" Vajon mivel magyarazhato Lantosnak ez a <br>pro-roman hajlama, amely szinte hajszalpontosan ugyanabban a <br>formaban jelentkezik most, 1996 nyaran, mint 1983-ban? Netan <br>Lantosnak "magyarproblemaja" van? Mi mas magyarazna azt, hogy a <br>ket millio magyart a legvalogatottabb eszkozokkel diszkriminalo <br>roman kormanyt egy amerikai kongresszusi kepviselo sajat magat es <br>a jozan eszt is megalazva, magasztalja es a legsulyosabb kommunista <br>gazembersegek folott szemet hunyjon? Netan egy titkon benne <br>lappango metafizikai kenyszer keszteti arra, hogy allandoan <br>bizonyitsa, milyen nagyvilagi eleganciaval tud felulemelkedni azon a <br>szuletesi veletlenen, amely erre a foldrajzi helyre szanta? Mely <br>kerdesre adando valasz, tekintettel Lantos funkciojara, nem egeszen <br>maganugy. A romanul kitunoen beszelo Funderburk, Eszak-Karolina <br>szovetsegi allam republikanus kongresszusi kepviseloje tobb <br>kepviselo- es szenatortarsaval egyutt tamogatja a Magyar Lobby <br>mostani tiltakozo akciojat. Nekik, a jelek szerint, nincs <br>"magyarproblemajuk". Szeretik viszont, ha az emberi jogokat es az <br>Egyesult Allamok torvenyes kotelezettsegeit betartjak - meg akkor <br>is, ha  magyarokrol, sot, megha a Romaniaban elo magyarokrol van <br>szo.   <br><br>==<br><br>MEGJEGYZESEK "AZ UJ ALKOTMANYSZABALYOZAS ELVEI"<br>CIMU ORSZAGGYULESI HATAROZATI JAVASLATHOZ<br>[Dr. Zetenyi Zsolt irasa a Nemzethez]<br><br>A magyarorszagi alkotmanyozasnak jelenleg tobb okbol nincsenek <br>meg a feltetelei, mert nem alakultak ki szilard es tartos politikai <br>ertekek, amelyek akar evtizedes szilardsagot nyujtanank egy <br>alkotmanynak.  Nem keszultek megfelelo elemzo tanulmanyok az <br>alkotmanyozasnak a magyar alkotmanytortenet es kozjog tenyeihez <br>valo kapcsolodasarol.  A torteneti alkotmanyok szellmisegevel nem <br>egyeztetheto ossze altalaban alkotmanyelvek keszitese, s kulonosen <br>sebteben es gyorsan elkeszitett chartak rakenyszeritese a <br>tarsadalomra.  Igen alapos elemzes utan minden alkotmanyozasi <br>folyamatban megfelelo hely illeti meg a magyar alkotmany es kozjog <br>tortenetet, kulonos tekintettel a Szent Koronatanra, amely korszeru <br>tartalommal kifejtheto es szervesen beleillesztheto egy megfelelo <br>idoben es modon lefolytatott alaptorveny elokeszitesebe.  Vegul, de <br>nem utolsosorban, az orszaggyules semmikeppen sem tekintheto <br>megfelelo alkotmanyozo testuletnek akkor, amikor sajat <br>jogositvanyait, vele kapcsolatban allo intezmenyek szabalyozasat <br>alakitja ki.  Elfogulatlan es targyilagos alkotmanyozas mindenkeppen <br>kulon testuletet igenyel.<br><br>Osszefoglalva: a helyzet alkotmanyozasra alkalmatlan, s ha alkalmas <br>lenne, akkor is a tortenelmi magyar alkotmanyba szervesen <br>beleillesztheto alkotmanylevel szukseges rovid, csiszolt tartalommal, <br>a reszletes szabalyozasnak sarkalatos torvenyekbe valo utalasaval.  <br><br>[Nemzet szerk. megjegyzes: A jogutod altal megszuntetett <br>Munkasorseg fegyveres bunozojenek "alkotmanya" csak arra lesz jo, <br>hogy annak papirjaval olyan tisztogato muveleteket vegezzenek majd <br>el, melyre mas papirt nem lenne meltanyos hasznalni. A <br>demokraciarol halvany fogalmuk sincs azoknak, akik a Orszaggyules <br>altal akarjak elkesziteni az Orszaggyules rendjet meghatarozo <br>Alkotmanyt. Hogy lenne elvarhato, hogy pl. a sajat PENZ erdekeiket <br>nezo kepviselok kimondjak a kepviselok szamanak drasztikus <br>csokkenteset, vagy azt, hogy hatalmukat biralja felul egy <br>ketkamarassa visszaallitott Parlament Felso Haza!? A Horn-Peto <br>alkotmany silanyabb es szegyenletesebb meg Sztalin-Rakosi <br>alkotmanyanal is - mert ugyan egyiket sem tartjak be a hatalom <br>bunozo birtokosai, de Rakosi legalabb (minthogy esze agaban se volt <br>betartani az Alkotmany egy sorat sem!) legalabb papirra vetett par <br>magasztos(nak hangzo) alapelvet. A Horn-Peto "alkotmanyozasban" <br>reszt vevo talpnyalo "ugyvedek" kicsit jobban vigyazhatnanak <br>magukra, mert kozremukodesuk dokumentuma lesz a Horn-Peto <br>hazaarulo kormanyzat kiszolgalasanak, es igy szemely szerint lesznek <br>felelossegre vonhatok!]<br><br>==<br><br>Miert nem talaljak a "szalmonellat"? <br>Mert Romaniabol hozott eper verhas-bakteriumai okoztak! <br>[Torgyan junius 10-i Parlamenti beszede]<br><br>DR. TORGYAN JOZSEF (FKGP): Koszonom a szot. Elnok Ur! Tisztelt <br>Kepviselotarsaim! A Fuggetlen Kisgazdapart orszaggyulesi <br>kepviselocsoportja helytallonak tartja a Fidesz gazdasagi ertekeleset, <br>de legyen szabad kiegeszitenem azt azzal a tennyel, hogy sajnalatos <br>modon ez a kormany nem akarja tudomasul venni, hogy mindaddig, <br>amig erezheto gazdasagi novekedest az elet minden teruleten el nem <br>tud erni, addig ennek a tarsadalomnak a melyrepulese meg tovabb <br>tart, hiszen azok a szembeotlo kormanyzati intezkedesek, amelyek az <br>inflacio tudatos gerjesztesebol fakadnak, nem intezhetok el olyan <br>felmondattal, mint ahogy azt a miniszterelnok ur tette, hogy 94 <br>szazalekos aremelesre szukseg volt a villamos-energia, illetve a <br>gazipar teruleten, hiszen ezzel szemben all az a kisgazda allaspont, <br>hogy miert kellett idegeneknek odaadni a mi villamosenergia-<br>iparunkat es gaziparunkat, akkor nyilvanvaloan nem lett volna <br>szukseg ilyen nagyaranyu aremelesre. De legyen szabad arra is <br>ramutatnom, hogy az eletnek nincs olyan terulete, ahol ne lenne <br>erzekelheto a felelotlen kormanyzati magatartas. Ilyen peldaul a <br>mezogazdasag teruleten most eszlelheto eperbehozatal akkor, amikor <br>Magyarorszagon a belfoldi termelest illetoen egy igen jo <br>eperidoszakrol szamolhatunk be, akkor hozzak be azt az olcso roman <br>epret, amely tobbek kozott a tomeges etelmergezest okozta. En ugy <br>gondolom, hogy latni kell, hogy addig, amig a kormany nem <br>hatarozza el magat a magyar erdekek megvedesere, addig a <br>gazdasagi folyamatokbol javitani nem lehet, ezt kerjuk szamon, es <br>koszonom elnok ur turelmet. (Taps az ellenzek reszerol.) (16.00)<br><br>==<br><br>Dow Jones Business News -- June 12, 1996 <br>PowerGen, GE Consortium To Build $300M Hungary Power Plant<br><br>BUDAPEST -- PowerGen PLC (PWG) has agreed with a consortium <br>comprised of General Electric Co. (GE) and Austria's ELIN <br>Energieversorgung to build a $300 million power plant in Hungary, <br>PowerGen Hungary officials said.<br><br>The project hinges on the successful completion of negotiations <br>between PowerGen and the Hungarian Electricity Works, the officials <br>said. The negotiations concern the long-term purchase of power and <br>the process of obtaining all required licenses and approvals, they <br>said.<br><br>The project is contingent on issues of power uptake and licensing, but <br>we're very hopeful,' said John Hunter, PowerGen Hungary's project <br>director.<br><br>PowerGen is asking MVM for a 20-year buying agreement, Hunter <br>said. If the negotiations are successful, the new power plant would <br>begin operating by 2000.<br><br>The 390-megawatt combined cycle plant, which would be managed <br>on a project finance basis, would be built on Budapest's Csepel Island. <br>The plant would provide both heat and electricity. The project <br>company would be Csepeli Aramtermelo Rt.<br><br>The development marks the further investment of all of the involved <br>companies in the Hungarian energy sector.<br><br>PowerGen bought a 95.5% majority stake in the 43-megawatt Csepeli <br>Eromu power plant in 1995.<br><br>GE and ELIN Energieversorgung recently finished building a Frame <br>9E gas turbine and a heat recovery steam boiler unit at the Kelenfold <br>power station in Budapest.<br><br>The Csepel plant would use modern gas technology to achieve high <br>levels of fuel efficiency and low emission levels, according to <br>PowerGen.<br><br>==<br><br>Wall Street Journal <br>June 12, 1996<br><br>By RICHARD F. STAAR<br><br>Before we become too sanguine about the prospects of a second term <br>for Russian President Boris Yeltsin, it's worth looking at a blueprint <br>for a new Russian defense strategy written by a group of Mr. <br>Yeltsin's security advisers. The report, commissioned by the Russian <br>government from the Institute for Defense Studies (known by its <br>Russian acronym, Inobis) and entitled "A Strategy to Neutralize <br>Threats to National Security," should give pause to even the most <br>optimistic outsider. "Most representatives of the power structures <br>(defense, security and police) are in agreement with our ideas," <br>Anton Surikov, the ex-military intelligence man who heads the <br>institute, told an Estonian newspaper.<br><br>The Inobis proposal starts from the premise that the U.S. and other <br>NATO members have been steadily encroaching on the Russian <br>Federation's vital interests in former strategic outposts of the Soviet <br>Union. In order to block these moves, Inobis recommends <br>establishment of a military alliance among former Soviet republics <br>(excluding Ukraine and the Baltics) and the deployment of tactical <br>nuclear weapons in three theaters of military operations: the western <br>(in Belarus and the Kaliningrad region and on warships on the Baltic <br>Sea), the northern (along the border with Norway and on the Barents <br>Sea) and the southern (at Russian bases in Crimea, Georgia and <br>Armenia and on the Black Sea).<br><br>If current flirtations between Russia and NATO (including several <br>joint maneuvers) should cool, Inobis recommends that Russia sell <br>nuclear and missile technology to Iran, Iraq and, if Islamic radicals <br>gain power, Algeria. The plan also envisages a possible military <br>alliance with Iran, in which Russia would deploy troops and tactical <br>nuclear weapons along the Persian Gulf and the Strait of Hormuz.<br><br>Would Mr. Yeltsin consider following these hard-line <br>recommendations? There's ample reason to think he would. In <br>January he appointed hard-liner Yevgeny Primakov (foreign <br>intelligence chief since August 1991) as foreign minister. The <br>following month, two senior advisers to the defense minister told a <br>Swedish military delegation in Moscow that Russian nuclear weapons <br>will be moved closer to the Nordic region and Central Europe if NATO <br>expands eastward.<br><br>Russia is increasing its military spending, even as it underfunds its <br>regular armed forces. This year the government allocated only $8.9 <br>billion--12% of Russia's budget--to the Defense Ministry, which had <br>requested $15.4 billion. At the same time, however, the "state <br>defense order"--money spent on research, development and <br>production of new weapons systems, which isn't part of the Defense <br>Ministry's budget--will total $11.7 billion, well over twice the 1995 <br>total of $4.8 billion.<br><br>Mr. Yeltsin also recently issued a decree reducing by 20% all <br>machinery and raw materials held in storage to cover wartime needs <br>of the military. A system initiated by Stalin, these so-called <br>untouchable reserves had been depleted during World War II and <br>subsequently replenished. Mr. Yeltsin's new policy dramatically <br>increases the resources available to the military-industrial complex, <br>whose 5.5 million employees work in more than 1,700 plants and <br>research and development centers.<br><br>At a recent Security Council meeting, Mr. Yeltsin reportedly ordered <br>his intelligence chiefs to accelerate closure of the technology gap with <br>the West by improving industrial espionage, a development FBI <br>Director Louis J. Freeh calls "ominous."<br><br>Despite the alleged shortage of funds for the military, Moscow has <br>continued a Soviet-era project to build a huge command-and-control <br>center for nuclear war at Mount Yamantau, near the city of Belorets <br>in the Urals, according to testimony by Adm. William Studeman, then <br>acting CIA director, before the Senate Select Committee on <br>Intelligence last year. An April 17 article in the Russian daily <br>Segodnia reports that work on the project is continuing.<br><br>In addition, at a Feb. 22 congressional briefing, the Defense <br>Intelligence Agency's director, Lt. Gen. Patrick Hughes, outlined the <br>continued production of new Russian offensive weapons systems. <br>Specifically, these include the following:<br><br>* The latest SS-25 modification (Topol M-2) intercontinental ballistic <br>missile has been flight tested and will go into series production this <br>year.    <br>* Already coming off the assembly line are miniature nuclear <br>weapons (weighing under 200 pounds), to be carried by a new, <br>highly accurate tactical missile for Russia's ground forces.    <br>* Seven quieter nuclear-powered Severodvinsk-class submarines, <br>being built to supplement the 13 Akula-class ones, will carry the <br>new D-31 submarine-launched ballistic missile.<br><br>Russia's air defense already boasts the only anti-ballistic missile <br>system in existence. The SH-11 is designed to detonate a nuclear <br>charge above the atmosphere and destroy incoming warheads, <br>whereas the SH-08 has high acceleration for intercepts inside the <br>atmosphere. Yet a recent U.S.-Russian "framework agreement" <br>reportedly would place even greater restrictions on the American <br>side than the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.<br><br>Despite everything, the U.S. continues to pour massive amounts of <br>money into Russia without adequate safeguards or inspections, <br>according to the U.S. General Accounting Office. Low-grade uranium, <br>under an $11.5 billion contract, could actually be coming to the U.S. <br>from stockpiles in the closed cities known as Krasnoiarsk-45, <br>Sverdlovsk-44 and Tomsk-7, rather than from dismantled Russian <br>warheads as agreed. Those warheads, in turn, would be used for the <br>new Topol M-2 and D-31. This huge outlay comes after 23 U.S. <br>government agencies committed $15.4 billion through the end of <br>1994 for 215 programs in the former Soviet Union--about half of it <br>in Russia--according to a December GAO report. In addition, the <br>World Bank and the International Monetary Fund, organizations to <br>which the U.S. is the largest contributor, have continued to extend <br>more loans to Moscow. The World Bank announced last month a $1 <br>billion credit to Russia, for a grand total of $6.5 billion to date.<br><br>Boris Yeltsin's hard-line approach may turn out to be nothing more <br>than election-year bluster. But should Mr. Yeltsin's hard-line <br>advisers manage to get their hands on some of the funding flowing in <br>from the West, future historians may well record that the U.S. helped <br>finance those who restarted the now-dormant Cold War.<br><br>Mr. Staar, a senior fellow at the Hoover Institution, is the author of <br>"The New Military in Russia: Ten Myths That Shape the Image" <br>(Naval Institute Press, 1996). A longer version of this article, with <br>Russian sources, will appear in the Summer issue of Orbis: A Journal <br>of World Affairs.<br><br>==<br><br>OMRI OROSZ VALASZTASI HIRADO<br><br>ZYUGANOV APPEALS TO MUSLIMS. Communist Party leader Gennadii <br>Zyuganov issued an appeal to Muslim voters in Sovetskaya Rossiya <br>on 13 June, shortly after President Yeltsin's trip to Tatarstan. In <br>criticizing Yeltsin's government, he singled out the invasion of foreign <br>religious groups and the spread of "Westernism and Americanism <br>that threaten our traditional way of life." People of different religious <br>faiths may, nevertheless, have much in common in their approach to <br>Russia's social and moral problems, he asserted. Zyuganov denounced <br>the past repression of Muslims for their religious beliefs and <br>promised that such things will not happen again. He pledged that <br>Muslims will be able to worship as they wish, including through <br>pilgrimages to Mecca. There are as many as 20 million Muslims in <br>Russia. -- Robert Orttung<br><br>ZHIRINOVSKY BIDS FOR COMMUNISTS. Appearing on Russian Public <br>TV (ORT) on 13 June, Vladimir Zhirinovsky used his last free airtime <br>slot to ask Communist voters for their support. He stressed that he <br>was never an anti-communist and that ordinary rank-and-file <br>Communists knew nothing about the crimes committed by the Soviet <br>leadership, such as Stalin's deal with Nazi Germany or what he called <br>Mikhail Gorbachev's agreement to "hand over" the country to the <br>West. He asked rhetorically whether Gennadii Zyuganov might not <br>become "a second Gorbachev," reminding viewers that earlier this <br>year, Zyuganov attended the World Economic Forum in Davos, <br>Switzerland. Zhirinovsky declared that his goals were similar to those <br>of the Communists: to help poor people, to strengthen Russia, and to <br>support the state sector, military-industrial complex, and security <br>services. "Communists of Russia, I ask you to think before you just <br>vote blindly for your leader. [...] Vote for me on 16 June, and I won't <br>become a traitor like Gorbachev, or the kind of traitor Gennadii <br>Andreevich Zyuganov may possibly become." In closing, Zhirinovsky <br>accused Zyuganov of cowardice for refusing to debate him on <br>television. -- Laura Belin in Moscow<br><br>LEADERS CONSIDER CREATING A NEW PARTY. Prime Minister Viktor <br>Chernomyrdin is thinking about transforming his movement, Our <br>Home Is Russia, into a formal political party, Rabochaya tribuna <br>reported on 11 June. He said that "a party is needed, you can't get <br>away from this" and the only remaining question is when to set it up. <br>Chernomyrdin claims branches in 85 of Russia's 89 regions and 6,000 <br>active members, Rossiiskaya gazeta reported on 13 June. Vladimir <br>Lysenko of the Republican Party has proposed uniting many of the <br>small pro-reform parties around Yeltsin, Segodnya reported on 11 <br>June. He believes that such a party could bring together centrist <br>politicians of all stripes under a "broad, non-politicized name," such <br>as the Party of Russian Progress. President Yeltsin has shied away <br>from direct links to former political organizations such as Democratic <br>Russia and Russia's Choice and it seems unlikely that he would want <br>to play a major role in Chernomyrdin's or Lysenko's proposed new <br>parties. In early April, Yeltsin said, "I cannot be a member of any <br>party as long as political struggle is splitting society." -- Robert <br>Orttung<br><br>MEDIA<br><br>ZYUGANOV CRITICAL OF ADS AND NTV. In his last pre-election press <br>conference on 13 June, Communist Party leader Gennadii Zyuganov <br>blasted the media's coverage of the campaign, especially on <br>television. Referring to President Yeltsin's frequent TV ads, Zyuganov <br>remarked, "A good product doesn't need to be advertised," adding <br>that "when you get up, Yeltsin is there [on TV] and when you go to <br>sleep, he is still there, which means he is not a good product." He also <br>commented on the behavior of NTV "Itogi" anchorman Yevgenii <br>Kiselev, who interviewed him on 11 June. "I thought I would be <br>invited to express my opinion and discuss the issues in a fair <br>dialogue with a journalist whom I respect; instead of that, I just felt <br>sorry for someone who is now obviously taking orders, repeating <br>without imagination the questions he hears in his ear piece," he said. <br>Kiselev conducted the interview in a surprisingly sarcastic and <br>hostile tone, repeatedly interrupting Zyuganov and mentioning <br>extremists within his coalition, such as Workers' Russia leader Viktor <br>Anpilov. -- Anne Nivat in Moscow<br><br>IZVESTIYA: RYAZAN COMMUNISTS LIMIT LOCAL DEMOCRACY. As <br>part of its campaign to warn readers about the possible consequences <br>of a Communist victory, Izvestiya on 11 July described the situation <br>in Ryazan after the Communists took control of 19 of the 23 seats in <br>the city legislature. The Communists changed the charter of the city <br>so that the mayor would no longer be elected directly, but by the <br>legislature from among its members. The paper sarcastically quoted <br>the first deputy head of the soviet, N. Korneeva, as saying that the <br>soviet chose the procedure that would "bring about democracy in <br>reality." Such an electoral procedure would make it impossible for <br>incumbent Mayor V. Markov, who is not a member of the legislature, <br>to run again. In a referendum conducted along with the legislative <br>election, voters supported the idea of direct elections by 67% to 32%, <br>but the results were invalid because not enough people participated <br>in the voting. Numerous citizen groups took up the campaign to <br>preserve direct elections, but the Communists ignored them. The <br>article concluded by pointing out that the Communists will have <br>difficulty paying for all the promises they are currently making, <br>while the current mayor has a much better chance of carrying out his <br>promises. -- Robert Orttung<br><br>"SURPRISE ENDING" TO YELTSIN ADVERTISEMENT SERIES. The final <br>installment in President Yeltsin's series of "I believe, I love, I hope" <br>commercials, which show ordinary people reminiscing about their <br>lives and explaining why they are voting for the incumbent, features <br>the president himself. The two-and-a-half minute advertisement <br>includes many photos of Yeltsin as a child and young man. He recalls <br>that he did not have any problems in school but admits that <br>occasionally "I was a bit of a hooligan." Photos show Yeltsin as an <br>athletic young man, and the president describes the various sports <br>he played and the volleyball team he coached in Sverdlovsk. There <br>are many pictures of Yeltsin with his wife and daughters, and the <br>president remarks that he "could not have endured" without the <br>support of his family at crucial times. Near the end of the <br>commercial, Yeltsin says, "The last few years were years of changes, <br>not easy, but very necessary, and important for the country." He <br>concludes, "On 16 June, we are all going to make a choice. We are all <br>going to choose not only our own fate but also the fate of our <br>children and grandchildren. We will determine the fate of our Russia. <br>We will undoubtedly win, without fail, because we believe, we love, <br>we hope." -- Laura Belin in Moscow<br><br>LEBED ADS SATURATE PRIME-TIME TV. Although a video promoting <br>Aleksandr Lebed's candidacy portrays him as a novice politician <br>without his own party or money (see OMRI Special Report, 12 June <br>1996), Lebed's paid commercials are among those most frequently <br>shown on major television networks. The short advertisements <br>follow two different formats. Some take advantage of Lebed's <br>distinctive voice. Dressed in civilian clothes, the candidate stands in a <br>field promising to make Russia "proud, wealthy, and beautiful," or <br>speaks from an armchair about stopping the war in Chechnya and <br>restoring order, as a clock ticks in the background. The other Lebed <br>advertisements feature actors playing ordinary people: fishermen, <br>construction workers, blacksmiths, sailors. In each commercial, <br>someone remarks regretfully that there is no truth in the country, or <br>no leader who can be trusted, or no one who can restore order. <br>Another then answers, "There is such a person. You know him," after <br>which Lebed's picture is shown. -- Laura Belin in Moscow<br><br>BIZARRE YAVLINSKII COMMERCIALS. Grigorii Yavlinskii's early paid <br>advertisements were very short and generally featured only the <br>words "I choose freedom" or "We choose Yavlinskii" next to the <br>candidate's picture. In the closing days of the campaign, however, a <br>series of bizarre Yavlinskii commercials have appeared. Set to music, <br>the lighthearted advertisements feature actors portraying people of <br>all age groups and occupations who sing about why they support <br>Yavlinskii; some sing in rap style, while others are dressed in <br>traditional folk costumes and dance choreographed routines. In one <br>spot, two elderly people play the accordion and balalaika. Another <br>clip shows a young man sitting at a desk dressed like a businessman; <br>after he sings about voting for Yavlinskii, he does a handstand on his <br>desk and then a backflip off the desk. The advertisements are <br>presumably designed to make Yavlinskii appear down-to-earth or <br>appealing to ordinary people; some of the singers refer to him as <br>Grigorii or Grisha. However, they seem out of character for Yavlinskii, <br>even undignified for a presidential candidate. Vladimir Zhirinovsky <br>has cultivated an outrageous image in the past--one commercial <br>before last year's parliamentary election showed him dancing with a <br>blonde in a disco--but even his recent advertisements have reflected <br>a more serious tone. -- Laura Belin in Moscow<br><br>MORE "VOTE OR YOU LOSE" ADS. The commercials produced by the <br>Central Electoral Commission in order to increase turnout among <br>young voters are broadcast frequently on all major networks. One of <br>the most creative is filmed in a gloomy futuristic style. About 20 <br>young people stand in a semi-circle; they scoop pails of water out of <br>the ocean, pass the pails from hand to hand, and then dump the <br>water back into the ocean. An overseer cloaked in shadows watches <br>them work. One young man takes a break from the drudgery to ask, <br>"What's with this work? What are we doing?" Another shrugs his <br>shoulders and says, "We didn't vote," after which the overseer <br>screams, "I voted for this!" and sprays the cringing young people <br>with a hose. The advertisement closes with the slogan "Vote or you <br>lose." -- Laura Belin in Moscow<br><br>ANALYSIS AND PREDICTIONS<br><br>PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN DID NOT CREATE MULTIPARTY SYSTEM. <br>Although many political scientists consider elections to be one of the <br>main stimulators for the creation of political parties, political scientist <br>Liliya Shevtsova argued in Komsomolskaya pravda on 11 June that <br>the current presidential campaign did not stimulate party formation <br>in Russia. She believes that Russia has no real political parties but <br>only "political clubs, support groups for individual leaders, and <br>'umbrellas' that corporative groupings use to realize their interests." <br>She paints the Communist Party of the Russian Federation (KPRF), <br>often described as Russia's only party, as a "movement of counter-<br>elites who were able to mobilize the semi-destroyed cells of the <br>former Communist Party." Within the KPRF, however, there are <br>incompatible tendencies that could split the party. Additionally, she <br>speculates that after a Yeltsin victory, some members of the KPRF <br>leadership could break away from their more active comrades to join <br>the government. Shevtsova cannot predict a time when party <br>formation will start in earnest. Various lobbies with narrow <br>corporative interests will play the role of a party system for the <br>foreseeable future. The party of power, in all its manifestations, will <br>continue to be the most influential party, she asserts. -- Robert <br>Orttung<br><br>OPPOSITION TAKES SOBER LOOK AT YELTSIN'S STRENGTHS. KPRF <br>State Duma member Yurii Ivanov argues in Pravda Rossii on 6 June <br>that Zyuganov supporters must objectively evaluate the strengths of <br>Yeltsin's candidacy. Besides the perks of being the incumbent, Yeltsin <br>benefits from two conditions. First, although the economy is in bad <br>shape, it is not critical enough to lead to a social explosion. <br>Additionally, the Chechen war has only had a local impact, on the <br>region and the families of the people serving there. Second, Yeltsin <br>has created a large number of social groups that support his rule. The <br>major fault line is not between employers and workers, but between <br>industrial sectors. Thus, the raw materials sector, railroad employees, <br>communication workers, bankers, consultants, small businessmen, <br>and small-time traders who shuttle back and forth across the border <br>importing goods support Yeltsin, while the military-industrial <br>complex, textile, and agricultural sectors back Zyuganov. Yeltsin has <br>also managed to buy off many of the regional elite with the <br>numerous power-sharing treaties he has signed. The article claims <br>that Yeltsin has the support of criminal groups. The Communists can <br>count on people hurt by the reforms, pensioners, and refugees. The <br>author reminds his readers that "life will not end" if the Communists <br>lose this election. -- Robert Orttung<br><br>CENTRAL ELECTORAL COMMISSION<br><br>In an interview with OMRI's Anne Nivat on 12 June, Central Electoral <br>Commission (TsIK) Deputy Chairman Aleksandr Ivanchenko argued <br>that the election will be fair and dismissed rumors that the second <br>round may be held on Wednesday, 3 July.<br><br>OMRI: What is the main difference between this election and the <br>1991 presidential election?<br><br>Ivanchenko: While in 1991, the majority of politicians criticized the <br>electoral law [in effect at that time], today none of them expressed <br>doubts about it or about its structure. We lawyers from the TsIK <br>have had a much easier job this time; this electoral campaign is <br>rather quiet. The number of contenders is smaller than [in 1991]; <br>only 11 people from the approximately 100 who tried to obtain the 1 <br>million signatures needed to register for the presidential race <br>succeeded. Six of them who [were denied registration and then] went <br>to trial did not obtain anything. Actually, the law worked [as it was <br>meant to]. To have only about 10 candidates [following Aman <br>Tuleev's withdrawal] for the presidency is proof that we have <br>managed to have a normal political system in Russia. Some of them <br>represent parties, the others are without any political affiliation--<br>people definitely have a choice. The campaign was conducted in a <br>normal way, without any major scandals.<br><br>OMRI: Will the election be fair, and if there is any fraud, whom will it <br>benefit, and at what level? Ivanchenko: The word "falsification" itself <br>is not a legal term, but a political word. From the point of view of the <br>law, I would like to stress that there are very strict public <br>monitoring mechanisms that don't allow the election results to be <br>falsified at the level of the polling station, let alone at the other <br>levels. In each polling station of the Russian Federation, we will have <br>at least 10 observers who will monitor the entire process from the <br>moment the sealed ballot box is opened until the very end of the <br>vote count. From the point of view of the openness of public <br>monitoring, our Russian law is now very similar to European and <br>even American electoral law. Moreover, from the technical point of <br>view, everything is planned, even very small details. Anyone who <br>wants to may obtain a copy of the official vote count in his polling <br>station. Each candidate can also calculate his own vote count at the <br>national level. The fact that this possibility exists requires no further <br>commentary. The vote count itself is becoming quicker, more precise, <br>and more professional; and, last but not least, we are now objective. <br>All those discussions and doubts about the work of the Central <br>Electoral Commission will probably disappear with time; within a few <br>years, people will even have forgotten all those things and will trust <br>us. The commission is composed of party representatives, who work <br>openly without any secrets. Of course, some violations of the law are <br>still possible, it is impossible to avoid them, but those cases will all <br>be solved by local courts; it might be that after a court decision, we <br>would change the result of an entire polling station. [...] We will begin <br>to deliver the results as soon as Kaliningrad [the westernmost <br>Russian region] has finished voting.<br><br>OMRI: What does the electoral law say concerning the second round? <br>Can it be on the 3 July, in the middle of a week, or not ? Ivanchenko: <br>This idea came from Sergei Filatov, head of Yeltsin's staff, but we did <br>not even discuss it in the TsIK. First, the law says that the vote <br>should take place on a weekend, thus, the second round, if there is <br>any, will definitely be on a weekend, but the law doesn't regulate <br>this point in detail. The more quickly we count the votes, the more <br>quickly we will get the results--it is possible that we will do it in <br>three days, we can do it very rapidly, but it still depends on things <br>like the planes coming from the regions with the original documents <br>of all the 89 subjects of the federation. If everything goes on <br>schedule and we receive those results within three days, of course, <br>we will rapidly set the second round for 30 June. We could also set it <br>for 7 or 14 July, but everything will depend on the speed at which <br>we receive the official results. But anyway, it may be that we won't <br>need a second round.<br><br>OMRI: How do you judge the electoral campaign, especially on TV? <br>Ivanchenko: The TsIK has been obliged to draft special instructions <br>for the work of the media during the electoral campaign because, <br>unfortunately, we don't have an adequate law on the electronic <br>media that regulates the work of the mass media in general, not only <br>during elections. It is very difficult to solve questions about the <br>media campaign, which lasts one month, when the general tasks of <br>the media have not been clarified for the rest of the year. Of course, <br>we have our own ideas about how the mass media should work, <br>about the way they should have covered this campaign, but we <br>realize that this can only be decided by a law. The TsIK alone is not <br>able to control this process: the procuracy [and] governmental organs <br>that work with the media should also participate in it. The only way <br>to regulate the media is to have [state bodies] work together. A law <br>regulating in detail the work of the media would have made our <br>work considerably easier.<br><br>CAMPAIGN DOCUMENTS<br><br>NATIONAL SOCIALISTS WILL VOTE AGAINST ALL. The Russian <br>National Socialists have joined the presidential campaign, but, in <br>contrast to many other parties that campaign in support of their <br>candidates, the National Socialists are urging their supporters to vote <br>against all of the nominees. Here is an abstract from an article <br>published in the radical national socialist newspaper Shturmovik No. <br>7-8, which was written by its founder and editor-in-chief Konstantin <br>Kasimovskii, who is also an ideologist of the fascist Russian National <br>Union (Russkii natsionalnyi soyuz).<br><br>[...] One thing is obvious: the real struggle will be only between <br>Yeltsin, who is more likely [to win] as an incumbent president since <br>he has concentrated power and propaganda tools in his hands, but <br>who is nevertheless unpopular among the "mass electorate," and <br>Zyuganov, who has a huge (according to today's standards) party and <br>a majority in the parliament behind him. [...] It is obvious that other <br>candidates have an extremely small chance of making it to the <br>second round [...]<br><br>Our "propaganda ministry," central television, realized this a long <br>time ago and skillfully uses [it] to make cretins out of the Russian <br>people. Realizing that the choice as such will be between democrats <br>and Communists, they [...] present an alternative: either Yeltsin, or <br>Zyuganov, with no other choice. But there is a third [option]...<br><br>There is a well-defined conception of the Third Way. Any political <br>scientist, who was not educated in the Institute for Marxism-<br>Leninism, where [they] teach you how to think with the opposite of <br>your head, knows that National Socialism and [other] political <br>systems close to it were always called the Third Way.<br><br>[...] National Socialism as a political organization cannot now compete <br>with either the Communists, who wield sausages costing only 2.20 <br>rubles [as an argument], or democrats [...]<br><br>Every day, I'm bothered with the question "who to vote for?" Our <br>position [...] is to vote against all. Bearing in mind that the main <br>struggle will be between Yeltsin and Zyuganov, let us try to <br>understand who is better for Russia among the two of them [...]<br><br>We [Russian National Socialists] evaluate a candidate's <br>appropriateness for the position of nominal head of state from the <br>point of view of the national good. The one who will be able to make <br>our country great deserves to be its head.<br><br>So whom can we consider worthy, or more precisely, why do we <br>think that none of the current contenders is worthy of becoming the <br>head of state?<br><br>The way Yeltsin is ruling the country can be seen with the naked <br>eye. The best indexes--the collapse of the economy, army, social <br>policy, etc.--speak for themselves. Besides, his ideological orientation <br>is clear to everyone, despite what some who see the recent <br>"Russification" in the government say. It is not significant for us who <br>will destroy the country: non-Russians who cannot pronounce [the <br>letter] "r" properly [derogatory reference to Jews] and have double <br>citizenship, or blue-eyed and blond bastards, or some subhumans <br>(ebautmen--from English "about" and "man") who do not deserve to <br>exist.<br><br>Zyuganov's candidacy, which has become an idol of the "patriotic <br>opposition," also does not inspire heroic deeds. It does not matter if <br>Yegorushka Gaidar says that "while East European Communists are <br>evolving into social democrats [...] our [Communists] become national <br>socialists." All this is rubbish. Zyuganov is not progressing toward <br>any national socialism. His present position is pure social democracy, <br>only slightly flavored with semi-nationalist features for easier <br>digestion. Those patriots who are KPRF fans and are skeptical about <br>my reasoning can read Zyuganov's interview on how he will fight <br>fascism after taking power [...]<br><br>But let us set aside these reasons. Those who have something on <br>their shoulders that does more than just swallow food will <br>understand all this on their own. They will understand also that, in <br>any case, the election results have been predetermined and the <br>squeal of the patriotic camp will change nothing.<br><br>Therefore, vote against all. This way it will also be possible to <br>determine the approximate number of those who are ready to <br>support us-- Russian National Socialists. [Those] who don't want to <br>waver between bourgeois democracy and Marxist democracy, but <br>those who give Russia another way, the way it must go toward the <br>zenith of its glory. -- Translated by Anna Paretskaya<br><br>THE BALLOT<br><br>THE BALLOT VOTERS WILL SEE ON 16 JUNE. The presidential <br>candidates will be listed in Russian alphabetical order and identified <br>on the ballot as follows:<br><br>BRYNTSALOV Vladimir Alekseevich. Date of birth 23 November <br>1946. Deputy of the State Duma of the Federal Assembly of the <br>Russian Federation. Resides in the settlement of Saltykovka, <br>Balashikhinskii Raion, Moscow Oblast. Belongs to the all-Russian <br>public organization "Russian Socialist Party."<br><br>VLASOV Yurii Petrovich. Date of birth 5 December 1935. Writer. <br>Resides in the city of Moscow. Belongs to the inter-regional public <br>organization "Popular Patriotic Party."<br><br>GORBACHEV Mikhail Sergeevich. Date of birth 2 March 1931. <br>President of the International Foundation of Social-Economic and <br>Political Research. Resides in the city of Moscow.<br><br>YELTSIN Boris Nikolaevich. Date of birth 1 February 1931. President <br>of the Russian Federation. Resides in the city of Moscow.<br><br>ZHIRINOVSKY Vladimir Volfovich. Date of birth 25 April 1946. <br>Deputy of the State Duma of the Federal Assembly of the Russian <br>Federation, leader of the faction "Liberal Democratic Party of Russia." <br>Resides in the city of Moscow. Nominated by the electoral association <br>"Liberal Democratic Party of Russia (LDPR)." Belongs to the Liberal <br>Democratic Party of Russia (LDPR).<br><br>ZYUGANOV Gennadii Andreevich. Date of birth 26 June 1944. Deputy <br>of the State Duma of the Federal Assembly of the Russian Federation, <br>leader of the faction "Communist Party of the Russian Federation." <br>Resides in the city of Moscow.<br><br>LEBED Aleksandr Ivanovich. Date of birth 20 April 1950. Deputy of <br>the State Duma of the Federal Assembly of the Russian Federation. <br>Resides in the city of Moscow.<br><br>(Aman Tuleev's name and biographical data will appear on the ballot <br>after Lebed's. However, Tuleev's name will be crossed off each ballot <br>by hand, since he officially withdrew from the race after the ballots <br>had been printed. Central Electoral Commission Secretary Aleksandr <br>Veshnyakov told OMRI that if voters nonetheless check the box next <br>to Tuleev's name, such ballots will be considered invalid.)<br><br>FEDOROV Svyatoslav Nikolaevich. Date of birth 8 August 1927. <br>Deputy of the State Duma of the Federal Assembly of the Russian <br>Federation. Resides in the city of Moscow. Belongs to the Party of <br>Workers' Self- Government.<br><br>SHAKKUM Martin Lyutsianovich. Date of birth 21 September 1951. <br>First vice-president of the International Foundation of Economic and <br>Social Reforms. Resides in the city of Krasnogorsk, Moscow Oblast.<br><br>YAVLINSKII Grigorii Alekseevich. Date of birth 10 April 1952. <br>Deputy of the State Duma of the Federal Assembly of the Russian <br>Federation, leader of the faction "Yabloko." Resides in the city of <br>Moscow. Nominated by the electoral association "Yabloko." Belongs to <br>the association "Yabloko."<br><br>A box labeled "against all candidates" will appear at the bottom of <br>the ballot. -- Laura Belin in Moscow<br><br>Compiled by Robert Orttung<br><br>This material  was reprinted with permission of the Open Media  <br>Research Institute,  a nonprofit organization with research offices in  <br>Prague, Czech  Republic. For more information on OMRI publications,  <br>please write to:   info@omri.cz <br>
